abstract: RICHMOND, Va., July 4. The observance of the day as a holiday is general. The banks, commercial exchanges, depots, national, State, and city courts and offices are closed. There is an almost entire suspension of business throughout the city, the streets presenting a Sunday appearance. The First Virginia Regiment left for Norfolk and Fort Monroe last night, and will spend the day in those places.

abstract: MONTREAL, Quebec, July 17. The Mekeown inquest was closed to-day. The jury, after an elaborate examination of the circumstances attending the homicide, acquitted Francis Kirkpatrick, private of the Sixty-fifth Regiment, who bayoneted McKeown, and fully exonerated him of any criminal culpability. abstract: HARRISBURG, July 22. A strike was inaugurated on the Middle Division of the Pennsylvania Railroad this morning, all the firemen and freight crews stopping work. A number of firemen seized the engines and run them to the round-house, where they now are, guarded by the strikers. Great excitement has existed in the neighborhood of the depot all day.

abstract: CHICAGO, Ill., July 22. There is no trouble as yet among the railroad employes in Chicago, but the indications are that it will not be long delayed if the difficulties in the East are not speedily settled. Railroad men of all classes are exceedingly uneasy, and although they say but little they are evidently deeply absorbed in contemplating the progress of the revolutionary movement westward.

abstract: BALTIMORE, Md., July 28.--The Baltimore and Ohio Railroad has to-day moved 23 freight trains between Baltimore and Cumberland, the first that have passed over the road for 11 days. Nine went west from Baltimore, 12 came east from Cumberland, and two east from Martinsburg. The trains from Martinsburg arrived here this evening without being interfered with anywhere along the line.

abstract: HARRISBURG, Penn., July 28.--Advices received at Gen. Sigfried's head-quarters in this city state that everything is quiet at Shamokin, Pottsville, and Shenandoah, and that no great fears of an outbreak are entertained.
